 Educational Background



DES Economics 
Class of 1970 


University of Paris

                  The University of Paris (French: Université de Paris) was a famous university in Paris, France, and one of the earliest to be established in Europe. It was founded in the middle of the 12th century and was officially recognized as a university from between 1160 and 1250 approximately.                




Graduate 
Class of 1964 


Robert College







 Career History



Partner/Chairman of ECL

                                    2005 - ?                


Egerton Capital (UK) LLP


                  Egerton is an active, research-intensive, benchmark agnostic manager which follows a long/short investment approach to invest in liquid, large-cap equities, diversifying across geographies and sectors. The firm employs a bottom-up strategy to identify undervalued equities with significant upside potential, constructing eclectic and uncorrelated portfolios. They employ little or no leverage and typically avoid companies which cannot grow through their own free cashflow on a sustainable basis. Their in-house fundamental research, which includes company visits, is complemented by external sources.                




Founding Partner & Chief Investment Officer

                                    Prior                


Beaumont Financial Partners LLC


                  Beaumont Financial Partners (BFP) believes that asset allocation is the single most important factor in achieving strong long-term performance. After determining the appropriate allocation of assets, they implement sector decisions and individual actions designed to generate performance results that will achieve or surpass the goals of their clients. The firm also believes that a top down asset allocation driven investment approach with superior global macroeconomic insight leads to top tier risk-adjusted investment results. BFP seeks to identify and select specific investments that will benefit from these value-creating themes and construct customized portfolios to meet each client’s unique objectives. BFP's investment approach begins with a consideration of all asset classes from a global macroeconomic standpoint to determine themes they think offer the best prospects on a risk/reward basis. Screening factors include historical market data, global demographic analysis, balance of trade and national debt comparisons, budget/deficit calculations, currency purchasing power parity analysis, global interest rates; and general supply/demand analytics across a wide array of commodities and materials. This process generates the themes/sectors BFP believes present the best investment opportunities for their clients and shape their rigorous asset allocation modeling. Once the themes/sectors are identified, BFP conducts additional fundamental, bottom up research and analysis on the specific investments (i.e., individual securities, mutual funds, ETFs, hedge funds, etc.). For the core equity component of client portfolios, BFP tends to focus on companies that have a history of generating significant free cash flow and sharing that cash flow with investors via their dividends. They prefer companies that have a long history of increasing their dividend annually and have a modest dividend payout ratio. In sectors in which they are more speculative, BFP’s analysis might focus on the value of a company’s assets and the discount these assets are valued at relative to the company’s stock price. Other value catalysts they look for include management changes, stock buyback plans, sectors that are consolidating, mispriced stocks due to market overreactions, and improving business models.BFP uses a method of categorizing the diverse investment universe which is referred to as the Dominant Benefit Theory of Investing. The Dominant Benefit Theory defines all investments into one of five categories based on the dominant characteristic of each investment. The categories are: safety, income, equity income, growth and aggressive growth.                




